1. STATIC KEYWORD
-------------------------------------------------------

Definition
----------
Static is a non-access modifier in Java.

The static keyword is used to create members that belong to the class instead of the object.

Static members are created only once in memory and are shared by all objects of the class.

Why do we use Static?
---------------------
1. Saves memory.
2. Only one copy is created.
3. Shared among all objects.
4. Can be accessed without creating an object.

Features of Static
------------------
• Belongs to the class.
• Memory is allocated only once.
• Shared by all objects.
• Can be applied to:
   - Variables
   - Methods
   - Blocks
   - Nested (Inner) Classes

-------------------------------------------------------
STATIC VARIABLE
-------------------------------------------------------

A static variable belongs to the class instead of the object.

Example:
--------
class Student{
    static String college="Tech High";
}

If 100 Student objects are created,
Only one copy of college is created.

-------------------------------------------------------
STATIC METHOD
-------------------------------------------------------

A static method belongs to the class.

It can be called using the class name.

Example:
--------
Demo.display();

No object is required.

-------------------------------------------------------
STATIC BLOCK
-------------------------------------------------------

A static block executes only once when the class is loaded into memory.

Example:
--------
static{
    System.out.println("Static Block");
}

-------------------------------------------------------
RULES OF STATIC
-------------------------------------------------------

Inside Static Method

✔ Can access Static Variables

✔ Can call Static Methods

✘ Cannot directly access Instance Variables

✘ Cannot directly call Instance Methods

-------------------------------------------------------
INSTANCE METHOD vs STATIC METHOD
-------------------------------------------------------

Instance Method

✔ Can access Instance Variables

✔ Can call Instance Methods

✔ Can access Static Variables

✔ Can call Static Methods


Static Method

✘ Cannot directly access Instance Variables

✘ Cannot directly call Instance Methods

✔ Can access Static Variables

✔ Can call Static Methods

-------------------------------------------------------
2. FINAL KEYWORD
-------------------------------------------------------

Definition
----------
Final is a non-access modifier.

It is used to prevent modification.

It can be applied to

• Variable

• Method

• Class

-------------------------------------------------------
FINAL VARIABLE
-------------------------------------------------------

A final variable cannot be changed after initialization.

Example

final int PIN = 1234;

PIN = 5678;

Error

-------------------------------------------------------
FINAL METHOD
-------------------------------------------------------

A final method cannot be overridden.

Example

final void display(){

}

-------------------------------------------------------
FINAL CLASS
-------------------------------------------------------

A final class cannot be inherited.

Example

final class Animal{

}

-------------------------------------------------------
FEATURES OF FINAL
-------------------------------------------------------

Final Variable
--------------
Cannot change value.

Final Method
------------
Cannot be overridden.

Final Class
-----------
Cannot be inherited.

-------------------------------------------------------
3. ABSTRACT KEYWORD
-------------------------------------------------------

Definition
----------
Abstract is a non-access modifier.

It is used to create incomplete classes and incomplete methods.

Abstract classes cannot have objects.

-------------------------------------------------------
ABSTRACT CLASS
-------------------------------------------------------

An abstract class is declared using the abstract keyword.

Example

abstract class Animal{

}

Object creation is not allowed.

Animal a = new Animal();

Error

-------------------------------------------------------
ABSTRACT METHOD
-------------------------------------------------------

An abstract method has no body.

Syntax

abstract void makeSound();

The child class must implement the method.

-------------------------------------------------------
WHY DO WE USE ABSTRACT?
-------------------------------------------------------

1. To achieve abstraction.

2. To hide implementation.

3. To force child classes to implement methods.

-------------------------------------------------------
FEATURES OF ABSTRACT CLASS
-------------------------------------------------------

• Cannot create objects.

• Can contain Constructors.

• Can contain Static Methods.

• Can contain Final Methods.

• Can contain Normal Methods.

• Can contain Abstract Methods.

• Can contain both Abstract and Non-Abstract Methods.

-------------------------------------------------------
IMPORTANT INTERVIEW QUESTIONS
-------------------------------------------------------

Q1. What is Static?

Static is a non-access modifier that belongs to the class instead of the object.

-------------------------------------------------------

Q2. Why do we use Static?

To save memory and share one copy among all objects.

-------------------------------------------------------

Q3. What is Final?

Final is a non-access modifier used to prevent modification.

-------------------------------------------------------

Q4. What is Abstract?

Abstract is a non-access modifier used to create incomplete classes and methods.

-------------------------------------------------------

Q5. Can we create an object of an abstract class?

No.

-------------------------------------------------------

Q6. Can an abstract class have constructors?

Yes.

-------------------------------------------------------

Q7. Can an abstract class have normal methods?

Yes.

-------------------------------------------------------

Q8. Can an abstract class have static methods?

Yes.

-------------------------------------------------------

Q9. Can an abstract class have final methods?

Yes.

-------------------------------------------------------
SUMMARY
-------------------------------------------------------

Static
------
• Belongs to the class.
• One copy for all objects.
• Saves memory.

Final
-----
• Variable → Cannot change value.
• Method → Cannot override.
• Class → Cannot inherit.

Abstract
--------
• Cannot create objects.
• Used to achieve abstraction.
• Child class must implement abstract methods.
• Can contain constructors, static methods, final methods and normal methods.

